<h1>SgbMap</h1>
<p>The main map component. Renders an interactive MapLibre GL JS map with configurable styles, controls, markers, shapes, and popups.</p>

<h2 id="basic_usage">// basic_usage</h2>
<p>Provide a center coordinate and zoom level. The default style is OpenFreeMap Liberty, a clean vector style that requires no API key. Pass <code>Controls</code> entries such as <code>new NavigationMapControl()</code> to render map controls. <code>FitBoundsOptions</code> auto-fits the viewport to a set of feature IDs.</p>
<ExampleView TComponent="BasicMapExample">
    <BasicMapExample />
</ExampleView>

<h2 id="fit_bounds_padding">// fit_bounds_padding</h2>
<p><code>FitBoundsOptions</code> fits the map viewport to a set of features. Use <code>Padding</code> for uniform spacing on all sides, or <code>TopLeftPadding</code> and <code>BottomRightPadding</code> for asymmetric padding when UI elements like sidebars overlap the map. The <code>CenterMapControl</code> button automatically reads the current <code>MapOptions</code> to re-center.</p>
<ExampleView TComponent="FitBoundsPaddingExample">
    <FitBoundsPaddingExample />
</ExampleView>

<h2 id="styles">// styles</h2>
<p>Swap between built-in style presets using the <code>MapOptions.Style</code> property. The library ships with <code>MapStyle.OpenFreeMap.Liberty</code>, <code>Positron</code>, and <code>Bright</code>. Use <code>MapStyle.FromUrl</code> or <code>MapStyle.FromRasterUrl</code> for custom sources. Because <code>MapOptions</code> is a record, change styles reactively with a <code>with</code> expression.</p>
<ExampleView TComponent="StyleSwitchingExample">
    <StyleSwitchingExample />
</ExampleView>

<h2 id="themes">// themes</h2>
<p>The <code>Theme</code> parameter controls UI chrome appearance (controls, popups, attribution). It has no effect on tile rendering. Pass <code>MapTheme.Dark</code> to switch to dark chrome. Hover the marker below and toggle themes to see the popup styling change.</p>
<ExampleView TComponent="ThemeSwitchingExample">
    <ThemeSwitchingExample />
</ExampleView>

<h2 id="markers">// markers</h2>
<p>DOM-based markers with optional drag, custom colors, and icons. Pass a list of <code>Marker</code> records to the <code>Markers</code> parameter. Key options include <code>Title</code>, <code>Color</code>, <code>Draggable</code>, <code>Scale</code>, and <code>Icon</code>.</p>
<ExampleView TComponent="MarkersExample">
    <MarkersExample />
</ExampleView>

<h2 id="circles_and_polylines">// circles_and_polylines</h2>
<p>GPU-rendered shapes for higher performance. <code>Circle</code> and <code>Polyline</code> records are rendered via MapLibre GL's WebGL pipeline. They render efficiently at large counts and support data-driven styling.</p>
<ExampleView TComponent="CirclesAndPolylinesExample">
    <CirclesAndPolylinesExample />
</ExampleView>

<h2 id="popups">// popups</h2>
<p>Three trigger modes: click, hover, and permanent. Attach a <code>PopupOptions</code> record to any <code>Marker</code> or <code>Circle</code> via its <code>Popup</code> property. Set <code>CloseButton: false</code> on permanent popups for a cleaner look.</p>
<ExampleView TComponent="PopupsExample">
    <PopupsExample />
</ExampleView>

<h2 id="wms_tile_layers">// wms_tile_layers</h2>
<p>Use <code>MapStyle.FromWmsUrl</code> to render WMS raster tiles as the base map style. Other factory methods include <code>FromWmtsUrl</code>, <code>FromArcGisMapServer</code>, and <code>FromRasterUrl</code>. To layer raster sources on top of a vector base, use <code>TileOverlay</code> instead.</p>
<ExampleView TComponent="WmsTileLayerExample">
    <WmsTileLayerExample />
</ExampleView>
